ck Webb, Dragnet’s creator, worked directly with the LAPD as he produced a series that would likewise inspire public trust by presenting day-to-day procedural justice, rather than shootouts and wild capers. Yet this realism also set aside the seething racial tensions of Los Angeles as it was. Dragnet emerges as a foundational text, one that taught audiences to see police as everyday heroes not only on TV but also in daily life, a lesson that has come under scrutiny as Americans increasingly seek to redefine the relationship between policing and public safety.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076651640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32538440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477325407423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477325407/original  a978-3-11-076651-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK